'''David Terence Puttnam, Baron Puttnam''', , , (born  ) is a film producer and politician.  He sits on the  benches in the .
He was educated at  in London and had an early career in advertising (see ) and acting as agent for the photographer . 
He turned to film production in the late 1960s.  His successes as a producer include '''', '''', '''' ('s feature film debut), '''' (which won the ), '''', '''', and '''' and '''' with  (which won the Palme D'Or at the Cannes Film Festival in 1986) mostly in association with .
He was Chair and Chief Executive Officer of  from 1986 to 1988. During his time at Columbia he was criticised for what some saw as a condescending attitude toward the Hollywood film industry, and for not sufficiently exploiting the studio's few box office hits. This strategic failure contributed to the sale of the studio to .
He was awarded a  in 1983, was knighted in 1995 and was created a  in 1997, as '''Baron Puttnam''', of Queensgate in the . In 2002 he chaired the joint scrutiny committee on the Communications Bill, which recommended an amendment to prevent ownership of British terrestrial TV stations by companies with a significant share of the newspaper market. This was widely interpreted as being aimed at stopping 's  from buying . When the government opposed the amendment, Puttnam brokered a compromise â€” the introduction of a "public interest" test to be applied by the new regulator , but without explicit restrictions. Puttnam is currently a trustee of the  the . In May 2006 he was made an Honorary Fellow of the Royal Society of Arts. In 2007, he chaired the Joint Parliamentary Committee on the Draft Climate Change Bill.
