He was for 10 years chairman of the  for many years, and taught people such as . He founded , which trains young people to become members of the film and television industries. In 2002 he was elected UK president of .
Lord Puttnam was the first chancellor of the  from 1997 until  . He was appointed an Honorary Doctor of Education during the School of Education and Lifelong Learning's Academic Awards Ceremonies in his final week as Chancellor and was granted the Freedom of the City of Sunderland upon his retirement. In 1998 he founded the National Teaching Awards and became its first chairman. He was the founding chairman of the General Teaching Council 2000-2002. He was appointed as chancellor of the  in 2006.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=Open University |date=2006-10-03 |url=http://www3.open.ac.uk/media/fullstory.aspx?id=9556 |title=The Lord Puttnam is appointed Chancellor of The Open University |accessdate=2006-10-08}}</ref> He was also the Chairman of NESTA (The National Endowment for Science, Technology and the Arts) from 1998 until 2003. He is also chairman of .
In 1982 he received the   Award for his outstanding contribution to the British Film Industry. In February 2006, he was awarded the  BAFTA Fellowship of the Academy. He made the occasion notable by delivering a particularly moving homage to his late father who had died before he received his Oscar for ''Chariots of Fire''.. He also congratulated contemporary filmakers (specifically ) for making films with integrity: the lack of such films being produced had been the reason for his retirement from the film industry in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brokeback emerges as Bafta winner |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4724066.stm |work=BBC News |date =   |accessdate=2006-10-08}}</ref>
